Differential diagnosis.
Distinguished from congeners by the inner lobe of the surstylus which is 6–7 times as long as wide and wedge shaped and the distal distiphallus, which has an asymmetrical, stout, leaf-like lobe that is sclerotized on the left and membranous with microtrichia on the right. The upper projection of the distiphallus is curled and slightly wider apically; the lower projection is short, thin, sclerotized and slightly reflexed (
Fig. 31
). Tergite 3 has a posterior band covering 1/6 to 1/4 the tergal length (
Fig. 27
). Females are here treated as indistinguishable.
